<TEXT>
wilbert lee evans who said he deserved 
another chance for helping prison workers during a deathrow 
escape was executed wednesday night in virginias electric chair 
for the 1981 murder of a sheriffs deputy 
evans 44 was put to death 3 hours after the us supreme 
court denied a stay of execution gov l douglas wilder also 
refused a request for clemency as evans awaited his execution at 
the state penitentiary 
evans was led into the death chamber in the prisons basement 
strapped into the electric chair and administered two 55second 
surges of 2500 volts each said wayne farrar spokesman for the 
state department of corrections 
he was pronounced dead at 1109 pm 
bart stapert assistant director of the virginia coalition of 
jails and prisons said he met with evans and the inmate told him 
i want to say to the family of mr truesdale im dead you dont 
have to hate me any more 
evans was sentenced to die for shooting alexandria deputy 
sheriff william truesdale on jan 27 1981 truesdale was returning 
evans to the alexandria jail after a hearing when evans grabbed the 
deputys gun and shot him 
the supreme court issued its ruling at 730 pm justice 
thurgood marshall who opposes capital punishment in all cases was 
the lone dissenter in the 81 vote 
evans attorneys based final efforts to save him on his actions 
during the may 1984 breakout of six death row inmates at the 
mecklenburg correctional center the lawyers contended that evans 
who did not join the escapees intervened to save prison guards and 
nurses from harm 
in his dissent marshall said a system of capital punishment 
that would permit wilbert evans execution notwithstanding 
astonow unrefuted evidence showing that death is an improper 
sentence is a system that cannot stand 
it was the 141st execution in the united states since the 
supreme court reinstated the death penalty in 1976 and the 10th in 
virginia 
in a letter handdelivered to the governors office wednesday 
afternoon evans attorneys presented evidence from an internal 
state police and corrections department report on the escape 
only you governor can prevent the commonwealth from foisting 
upon wilbert evans tonight an unconstitutionally cruel and unusual 
punishment said the letter signed by attorney arthur f mathews 
the letter included excerpts of statements from prison guards 
and nurses that evans protected them during the escape one nurse 
said evans stopped inmates earl clanton and linwood briley from 
molesting her 
of the escapees clanton briley and his brother james briley 
have been executed the other three remain on death row 
evans said wednesday in a telephone interview from the 
penitentiary that he was keeping busy doing legal work writing 
his will and conferring by telephone with his attorneys 
youve got to keep your hope up he said 
evans described his feelings as a mixture of hope and caution 
clamminess and nervousness 
last saturday us district judge robert r merhige jr granted 
evans a stay merhige concluded the trial jurys finding of future 
dangerousness as a reason for imposing the death sentence was 
thrown into question by evans actions during the mecklenburg 
incident 
a threejudge panel of the 4th us circuit court of appeals 
overturned the stay tuesday the appeals panel accepted the states 
argument that evans was seeking clemency a matter for the 
governor not a question for the courts 
 
</TEXT>
