<TEXT>
floridas top banking regulator 
accepted campaign contributions from directors of 40 percent of the 
financial institutions that have failed in the state since 1985 a 
newspaper reported wednesday 
since 1985 39 financial institutions supervised by comptroller 
gerald lewis the only elected state banking regulator in the 
country have failed 
the directors of 16 contributed to lewis reelection campaigns 
beginning in 1982 the miami herald reported from 1982 through 
this year lewis received more than 25000 from those directors 
it said 
in at least five cases lewis received contributions from 
businessmen who later received permission to open statechartered 
institutions the newspaper said 
among his backers were the directors of two of the states 
largest sampls centrust in miami and first american bank and trust 
in north palm beach both of which failed this year 
republican chris comstock who is vying for lewis post said 
the democratic incumbent has compromised himself by taking of 
huge amounts of money from the people he regulates 
lewis the states chief financial officer since 1974 said he 
could not recall specific details of campaign contributions made 
eight years ago he said no contribution ever influenced his 
decisions 
his office could not prevent the bank failures lewis said 
if we closed down those institutions it shows we did act 
lewis said the fact is that we have taken aggressive actions 
against institutions that failed 
the sampl crisis is expected to cost taxpayers billions of dollars 
nationwide florida has one of the highest sampl failure rates in the 
country 
in september 1982 fort lauderdale businessman scott gettemy 
gave 3000 to lewis campaign the maximum allowed by state law 
in 1984 the intercapital savings bank was incorporated with 
gettemy as a director according to state records it failed two 
years later 
miami businessmen said haddad juan martinez raul sanchez ma 
schofman and cayetano midolo gave thousands of dollars for lewis 
1982 reelection less than two years later they opened the trust 
bank which failed in 1988 
the newspaper cited three other similar cases 
comstock a financial adviser in st petersburg who worked as a 
bank examiner for the new york state department of banking before 
moving to florida in 1982 said the donations created conflicts of 
interest 
it tends to prevent him from acting promptly when the 
situation warrants comstock said i dont think hes done a 
good job regulating banks 
</TEXT>
