<TEXT>
a judge who imposed a gag order on 
coverage of a murder trial then ordered reporters not to report 
the gag order has changed his mind 
the daily press of newport news ignoring a prohibition by 
circuit judge morris b gutterman reported both his gag order and 
the order against reporting that he imposed it the newspaper also 
appealed the order joined by the richmond timesdispatch the 
richmond news leader and the virginianpilot and the ledgerstar of 
norfolk 
gutterman lifted his orders after the newspapers attorneys met 
with him in his chambers tuesday 
the action seems beyond belief to me said rod smolla a law 
professor at the college of william and marys marshallwythe 
school of law and director of the institute of the bill of rights 
law 
it seems to me that it is unconstitutional for a judge to 
issue a gag order on the press in a criminal trial then to issue a 
second gag order to keep the first secret only compounds the 
problem he said 
smolla said hed never heard of a judge issued a gag order over 
his own gag order 
gutterman declined to comment on the case 
david c kohler an attorney representing richmond newspapers 
inc said gutterman was concerned about what the jury in the 
murder trial of herbert g fisher might see in the newspapers 
fisher is accused of killing his wife 
when the trial opened monday and the jury was out of the 
courtroom gutterman ordered reporters not to make public any 
courtroom activity that the jury did not see 
juries often are taken from the courtroom while attorneys argue 
points of law such as what evidence the jury should hear 
gutterman also ordered reporters not to publish any account of 
his order 
we thought it was clearly unconstitutional prior restraint 
said jack davis editor of the daily press and we didnt think 
we needed to abide by it 
kohler said the us supreme court has set out strict rules 
concerning gag orders in a 1973 ruling on a nebraska murder trial 
the high court set out three criteria before judges can restrict 
coverage of criminal trials a compelling reason for such an order 
no alternative and effectiveness 
</TEXT>
