<TEXT>
the sandinistas bullied private 
businesmen for a decade while in power and are taking them on 
again this time as competitors 
they dont show up at chamber of commerce luncheons yet but 
many former sandinista leaders who once espoused marxism are now 
eyeing profit margins 
a lot of this is going on though exactly how much is not clear 
estimates of the number of sandinista companies range from 20 or 30 
to nearly 300 but there are no official records 
the source of the money is also in doubt president violeta 
chamorros government found the treasury nearly empty when it took 
over in april 
the companies are legal said a government official who 
spoke on condition of anonymity the question is where they got 
the means 
sandinista commercial interests now include stores newspapers 
radio stations farms real estate exportimport corporations and 
a television station some are owned outright by the sandinista 
front fsln and others by members with the front as a minority 
stockholder 
there is nothing wrong with a political party being in 
business within the framework of free enterprise said herti 
lewites the former sandinista tourism minister who is setting up 
some of the enterprises 
if i can make every member of the fsln rich i will he 
said 
lewites acknowledged that some marxist activists find the sudden 
entrepreneurial impulses of their fellows perplexing 
some of our militants and people in the government cannot 
quite assimilate this yet he said 
one of the most visible sandinista enterprises is central 
american airlines or caal which is to begin miamimanagua flights 
beginning oct 27 using a rented boeing 727 at the outset 
the airlines will charge 275 roundtrip the lowest fare between 
the two cities among carriers serving the region the ticket is to 
include free cocktails 
there is no reason why within a year we should not be flying 
to europe also said lewites the airline eventually plans 
flights to los angeles and san francisco mexico city madrid 
spain and london 
lewites has variously described the companys investors as saudi 
arabians greeks and lebanese 
in an interview last week he said the sandinista front had a 25 
percent interest in the airline and his personal stake was 3 
percent 
but at wednesdays news conference officially launching the 
airline lewites said there was no sandinista ownership 
i dont think even hertis grandmother believes that 
snickered a journalist from the cuban governments prensa latina 
news agency 
the sandinistas led the long struggle that overthrew the late 
president anastasio somzoa in july 1979 many of their leaders 
espoused marxist ideology and had trained in communist countries 
while in power the sandinistas frequently promised to support a 
mixed economy with plenty of room for private investors in 
practice the government seemed to make its economic policy as it 
went along nationalizations of companies and land often appeared 
arbitrary or aimed at political enemies 
the sandinistas economic policies and a ussponsored 
guerrilla war destroyed the economy 
when the sandinistas ran in free elections in february te 
voters rejected them for a more conservative coalition led by mrs 
chamorro 
most of the sandinista companies are headed by former government 
officials some of whom had left family businesses to join the 
sandinista revolution 
opponents claim some of the companies were stolen or set up with 
government funds and equipment sandinista officials have said the 
party squirreled away money supplied over the years by sympathetic 
foreign governments and other sources 
some businesses require little or no investment fernando 
guzman a former sandinista front official has the party as a 
minority partner in several companies including two importexport 
firms 
the fsln helped me get some of the contacts he said 
the sandinistas established trading companies in the united 
states panama and elsewhere years ago to circumvent the us 
embargo on trade with nicaragua 
manuel espinoza who was former president daniel ortegas press 
officer obtained a concession for a television station before the 
sandinistas left power 
as lewites put it the party must have resources things must 
change we cannot live off politics alone 
we are going to give the party a new image he added we 
are eliminating old taboos 
