the radioactive hulk of a 
semisubmerged soviet ship in a lake near the finnish border poses 
a major environmental hazard a finnish radiation safety official 
said today 
we have every reason to be worried and urgently need more 
information about the hulk said olli vilkamo senior inspector 
at the finnish center for radiation and nuclear safety 
the germanbuilt ship sunk in lake ladoga 30 miles from the 
finnishsoviet border was reportedly used in soviet secret 
military experiments during the 1950s 
lake ladoga supplies drinking water for 5 million people in 
leningrad the secondlargest soviet city it is the largest 
freshwater lake in europe 
finnish officials first learned of the existence of the 
radioactive hulk from finnish television journalists who had 
obtained a sovietmade documentary on the subject vilkamo said 
finnish television broadcast the film tuesday 
the soviet report said the ship contained 2000 tons of 
radioactive water containing strontium 90 a deadly substance 
present in fallout from nuclear explosions 
if the reports are true then its a lot and definitely 
there is a great risk here strontium 90 is extremely dangerous 
great caution has to be exercised in moving the hulk or pumping out 
the radioactive water vilkamo said 
finnish officials will assist soviet authorities in every way 
possible vilkamo said but added that they have their own very 
good experts and we are confident they can deal with it 
a treaty between finland and the soviet union obliges the two 
countries to report accidents and radioactive leaks to one another 
