commitment to stand by people with aids 
it is fair to say that aids is nothing less than a national 
crisis 
the city council voted 111 tuesday to adopt a policy that 
declares aids a natural disaster and a global emergency 
about 112000 people in los angeles county are infected with the 
aids virus and more than 60000 of those people live within the 
city limits the document said 
the policy calls for increased spending on acquired immune 
deficiency syndrome at all levels of government city departments 
have six months to plan implementation and determine costs the 
community development department was ordered to estimate the 
policys longterm fiscal implications 
the document outlines new problems such as training for city 
employees and distribution of aids prevention kits including 
condoms and hypodermic needlecleaning bleach kits to people being 
released from jail 
the county not the city runs the jail system and the county 
board of supervisors has twice gone on record against public 
distribution of condoms and bleach kits 
the blueprint reinforces the citys stand against 
discrimination the position that aids patients have a right not to 
disclose their condition and that casual contact doesnt spread 
aids it gives city employees the right to withhold information on 
whether they have the disease 
the policy also affirms that everyone with the disease has a 
right to dignity respect civil rights and a choice of care and 
treatment options 
the policy urges the federal government to reverse immigration 
policies that exclude people who test positive to the hiv virus 
that causes aids it also opposes mandatory hiv testing and mass 
quarantines of aids patients 
