<TEXT>
amnesty international on thursday called on the 
central african republic to charge or release more than 30 
government opponents detained without trial 
the detainees included gen francois bozize a former government 
minister who leads the opposition peoples movement for the 
reconstruction of the central african republic they also included 
abel goumba leader of the opposition obangui patriotic frontlabor 
party amnesty international said 
the government has denied rumors that bozize died in custody 
bozize and 11 others have been held without trial for more tha 
a year after being forcibly repatriated from benin they were 
allegedly connected with a coup attempt in march 1982 the human 
rights group said in its report 
officials in benin arrested the men in the capital of cotonou on 
july 24 1989 and handed them over to central african republic 
authorities the following month said the report published 
thursday 
the repatriation appears to have taken place without any 
formal extradition procedures being followed it said 
amnesty international said the government initially said the men 
were wanted in connection with the coup attempt but later alleged 
they had planned to sabotage fuel and electric installations and 
carry out assassinations 
they are being held in military custody without access to 
lawyers or family and some have reportedly been beaten and 
illtreated the report said 
bozizes younger brother honorat ouilebona cocksiss also has 
been held since his arrest dec 29 1989 michel ngouni an air 
