<TEXT>
here is a comparison of soviet economic plans one proposed by 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev and the other backed by 
russian president boris n yeltsin the soviet legislature is 
expected to pass the gorbachev plan perhaps as early as saturday 
and the russian legislature already has passed the more radical 
approach advocated by yeltsin 
 
pricesequals 
gorbachev plan onethird of all prices would be controlled by 
central authorities instead of nearly all as at present the 15 
soviet republics will have the right to raise prices for certain 
goods in accordance with local conditions and freeze prices if they 
rise out of control by 1992 only prices of staples such as bread 
meat and dairy products will still be fixed welfare payments would 
be indexed to price increases 
yeltsin plan the market rather than administrative decree 
would determine prices on many goods there would be gradual 
increases in wholesale prices of energy prices would be frozen on 
100 to 150 basic goods and services for the entire transition 
period after that the prices of 70 percent to 80 percent of goods 
would be free floating some rationing is not ruled out and some 
social assistance will be provided 
 
privatization of businesses and propertyequals 
gorbachev plan privatization of small businesses the plan 
drops reference to widescale ownership of private property 
gorbachev separately has called for a referendum on 
decollectivization of agricultural land 
yeltsin plan would end state control over businesses and 
property with the private sector prevailing in most industries and 
private citizens not agencies as property holders some property 
would be sold at low or symbolic cost to labor collectives leasing 
might be possible as would be private family property but the 
republics would determine some forms of ownership 
 
budget financingequals 
gorbachev plan federal budget would be financed through 
federal taxes republics and localities would also have the right 
to levy taxes a central bank would be created to control money 
supply and credit and the ruble would be the only legal tender 
throughout the country 
yeltsin plan strict control on state spending reform of the 
banking system russia would issue its own currency 
 
central controlequals 
gorbachev plan central government to retain control of 
defense energy production nuclear power highway and rail 
systems space exploration maritime affairs republics would 
control their own resources although details apparently would be 
left to a proposed interrepublic economic committee with as 
yet undefined enforcement powers 
yeltsin plan economic union would be on a voluntary basis 
central government would control most national security affairs 
although not all foreign relations republics largely would control 
their own energy resources 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

