<TEXT>
congressional negotiators reached a tentative 
accord wednesday on controlling emissions toxic industrial 
chemicals leaving them only one big step away from agreement on a 
costly new clean air law 
still on the table was the question of how to deal with acid 
rain the last barrier to the first major overhaul of national air 
pollution law in 13 years 
wednesdays agreement represents the first time the government 
would require businesses to make dramatic reductions in the more 
than 24 billion pounds of 189 hazardous chemicals including many 
cancercausing agents released yearly into the air 
reductions would be required not just from factories refineries 
and chemical plants but also from smaller businesses such as dry 
cleaners and furniture refinishers and even from garbage 
incinerators 
sen david durenberger rminn who led senate negotiators on 
the industrial emissions section of the bill said he believed an 
acid rain agreement could be reached by the end of the week 
rep gerry sikorski dminn said he expects attempts by 
midwest lawmakers to push for additional measures to reduce the 
cost of meeting new acid rain controls but he said negotiators of 
all points of view who want to get a bill enacted into law will 
not put up with a lot of grandstanding at this point 
wednesdays compromise followed long closeddoor negotiations 
often late into the night against the deadline of an oct 26 
adjournment that began last weekend and for a time were bogged 
down over whether to give the steel industry additional time to 
comply with the new pollution controls 
it was agreed to give steel companies another 20 years to the 
year 2020 to cut cancercausing emissions from coke ovens the 
industry had argued the ovens would be forced to shut down without 
the extension 
the negotiations immediately turned to the bills acid rain 
provision which would require electric utilities to cut annual 
emissions of sulfur dioxide by 10 million tons by the end of the 
decade 
the bush administration has estimated the bill if enacted 
would cost the economy between 21 billion and 25 billion a year 
once fully in effect environmentalists argue much of that amount 
will be gained in reduced health care costs from cleaner air 
congressional sources said wednesday that while some minor 
issues remained to be worked out house and senate members agreed 
on requiring industry to install new equipment aimed at cutting 
toxic emissions from large factories by 90 percent over the next 
decade 
toxic chemical emissions from smaller polluters would be reduced 
by about 75 percent the emissions cuts would be achieved by 
requiring companies to install the most effective pollution control 
technology available for a particular industry 
under the compromise the environmental protection agency also 
would be required to direct polluters to take additional measures 
after the turn of the century if the agency determines people near 
industrial plants are not being assured of an ample margin of 
safety against cancercausing pollution 
if those assurances are not met plants could be closed 
the legislation would regulate more than 250 types of pollution 
sources in addition the compromise would for the first time 
require new safeguards and response programs in the event of 
accidental releases of toxic chemicals 
both the house and senate approved clean air bills by a wide 
margin earlier this year but the conference committee negotiations 
aimed at resolving differences in the bills has at times slowed to 
a virtual standstill 
a breaktrough came oct 10 when the two sides reached agreement 
on measures to reduce smogcausing pollution from automobiles and 
trucks 
</TEXT>
