gorbachev is scheduled to defend his plan in a speech to the 
national legislature on friday the 542member supreme soviet could 
vote on it as early as saturday although some lawmakers said a 
longer debate was likely 
the fourstage gorbachev plan would begin by reducing the 
national budget deficit now about 100 billion and cutting the 
money supply which has grown rapidly in recent years spurring 
inflation 
western experts estimate soviets have saved billions of dollars 
worth of rubles in banks or under their mattresses because there 
is little to buy in state stores 
efforts also would be made in the first stage to improve 
production of consumer goods now in short supply and to boost 
agricultural output through land reform 
each republic would be allowed to decide whether to break 
collective farms into private plots in the second stage at an 
unspecified date prices on roughly 70 percent of all goods and 
services would be freed to respond to market forces the central 
government would continue to set prices on fuel key raw materials 
and necessities such as bread milk and sugar 
small private businesses also would be encouraged during the 
second stage and a social welfare net would be established to help 
workers who lose their jobs 
the third stage would emphasize establishing a free market for 
housing a modern banking system and entrepreneurship 
the final stage would end government monopolies in many 
industries and allow the ruble to be freely traded against other 
world currencies encouraging foreign investment in the soviet 
union 
unlike the 500day plan gorbachevs proposal contains no time 
schedule it says that similar transitions in other countries have 
taken 1 to 2 years 
growing shortages of staples such as meat gasoline and paper 
have eroded public support for gorbachev and skepticism over his 
plan appears widespread 
i think in the existing situation all the plans for economic 
reform are unrealistic said ninel ilyicheva 55 a publishing 
house worker i dont see that gorbachev is really accomplishing 
anything i only hear him talk and talk and talk all the time 
vladimir orlov 46 a soviet army major said he considers 
gorbachev a smart person who hasnt said his final word yet 
on the economy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

