<TEXT>
the senate has passed a bill directing the 
government to pay 35 million to the seneca indians admitting that 
congress wrongly forced the tribe to lease its land for 115 years 
to the city of salamanca ny 
we took advantage of the seneca nation and now we ought to 
correct this injustice said sen daniel p moynihan dny who 
introduced the bill in the senate along with sen alfonse damato 
rny 
the senate passed the measure by voice vote late tuesday the 
bill originally sponsored by rep amo houghton rny passed the 
house on oct 10 
administration officials however have said the government is 
not financially liable for the low rents paid to the senecas and 
they oppose the measure because of its cost president bush has 10 
days in which to sign it veto it or simply allow it to pass into 
law unsigned 
the bill would ratify an agreement reached by salamanca three 
nearby villages and the seneca nation to replace a 99year lease 
accord expiring feb 19 1991 
the lease arrangements date to the 1860s and 70s when whites 
moved onto seneca lands in western new york to work on railroads 
and drill for oil they leased the land at extremely low rents from 
individual senecas 
in 1875 congress confirmed these leases despite their dubious 
legality fifteen years later congress extended the leases for 99 
years with no provision to raise the rents 
thus about 85 percent of the city of salamanca is leased from 
the senecas at rents that were frozen as low as 1 per year 
