a critical meeting of yugoslavias 
federal parliament was postponed wednesday and the defense minister 
denied a military coup was planned if the legislature remained 
split along ethnic lines 
the postponment of the session until friday following a full 
day of procedural wrangling was seen by most observers as a clear 
victory for the reformminded republics of croatia and slovenia 
the session was meeting to discuss whether yugoslavia would 
remain a federation which serbia advocates or a loose 
confederation which croatia and slovenia back 
the latest ethnic standoff had threatened to block the 
parliamentary session sparking a constitutional crisis and 
deepening the political chaos menacing the country 
the parliament also voted 125 to 40 wednesday to confirm stipe 
mesic as croatias new representative on the federal presidency 
serbian deputies earlier threatened to refused to seat mesic 
seen by many serbs as a croatian nationalist as croatias member 
in the eightmember presidency croatian deputies reacted by 
warning they would walk out of parliament 
the serbs were finally outvoted by a block of slovenian 
croatian bosnian and macedonian representatives 
