<TEXT>
the house voted wednesday night to normalize 
trade relations with czechsolovakia for the first time since world 
war ii and dramatically reduce tariffs on its exports to the united 
states 
by a voice vote the house approved a trade agreement signed 
last april by the bush administration and the newly elected prague 
government granting each other mostfavorednation trade status 
such a status qualifies the exporting country for the lowest 
tariffs in effect on the goods it ships to the buying country 
the agreement now goes to the senate where approval also is 
needed before barriers to trade with the formerly communist ruled 
czechs can come down 
although the agreement was signed in april president bush did 
not send the agreement to capitol hill for the required 
congressional approval until last month 
the accord will effectively reduce by 90 percent the tariffs 
paid on some 82 million in czech exports to the united states last 
year and open the way for increased business ties between the two 
countries 
the effect will be to give czechoslovakia a much broader us 
market for its exports by cutting their prices to wholesalers 
retailers and ultimately american consumers by as much as up to 40 
percent 
it also will open the czech economy to more us exports while 
also protecting american companies patents and copyrights 
the agreement is the first us bilateral trade accord with a 
former eastern bloc country since the warsaw pact began collapsing 
more than a year ago 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

