<DOCNO> AP901017-0115 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
five years ago ohio voters approved a 
bond issue to find ways to clean the states highsulfur coal and 
in the process save the jobs of miners like jerry back 
some 85 million later back is anything but reassured 
ive got 15 years here and id hate to see it go down the 
drain back said as he prepared for the start of the second shift 
at the meigs no 2 mine i think in five years we may be 
working but i dont think well be working after five years 
ohios highsulfur coal once burned in many of the regions 
electrical power plants fell into disfavor in the 1980s amid 
rising concern about acid rain pollution state officials seeing 
the market diminish asked voters in 1985 to approve a 100 million 
bond issue to back research projects aimed at finding a way to 
remove some of the sulfur 
while officials say the research is promising the solutions may 
not gain widespread commercial acceptance in time to save many ohio 
mines and the jobs of 6700 miners 
im a coal miner but im a person too said miner bill 
oiler if there is a problem out there we do need to find a 
solution but the solution is not to just do away with jobs we 
need to find technology to alleviate the problem 
ohio coal development office chief jacqueline bird said her 
office has disbursed about 85 percent of the money raised through 
the 1985 bond issue some of the projects will soon enter 
largescale testing while others remain on the drawing board 
if there were a quick easy solution god knows we would have 
done it by now ms bird said were trying to find the 
permanent solution if there were a shortterm answer we would 
have landed on it 
ohio coal is abundant the ocdo estimates a 200year reserve 
but it is loaded with sulfur which combines with oxygen during 
burning to form sulfur dioxide sulfur dioxide combines with 
hydrogen and oxygen in the atmosphere to form sulfuric acid 
typical ohio coal has a sulfur content of about 35 percent 
most utilities need coal with sulfur content below 07 percent 
the federal government has steadily tightened sulfur dioxide and 
nitrogen oxide emission limits and even more stringent limits are 
pending in congress as the limits have shrunk so have ohio coal 
sales and mining jobs 
even ohios own utilities and mills burn more coal from out of 
state than instate mines last year less than 46 percent of the 
coal burned in ohio came from within the state us department of 
energy figures show 
but it takes as long as 25 years for a technology to move from 
concept to commercial acceptance ms bird said each stage must be 
tested and the next step revised on the basis of earlier findings 
and even when the technology is proven it takes time for the 
industry to trust it and invest millions of dollars in plant 
renovations she said 
ohio doesnt lack ideas at lorain it is testing a process that 
burns limestone along with coal to absorb sulfur dioxide 
at a plant in brilliant which was shut down in the 1970s because 
of the cost of complying with clean air laws theyre turning water 
to steam by burning a mix of coal and sorbent which reacts with 
and captures sulfur 
the steam drives a turbine and creates electricity but the 
gases from the burning are cleaned of sulfur and then used to 
create electricity in a second turbine remaining hot gas is used 
to heat fresh water headed into the boiler 
but jack segall us department of energy deputy assistant 
secretary for coal technology said there are no rewards for taking 
risks in new technology 
if the cost of producing electricity as a result of this new 
technology goes down its the ratepayer who gets the benefit he 
said if the technology does not work its the utility that gets 
penalized 
president bushs clean air plan includes incentives to encourage 
use of clean coal technologies segall said but its still not 
clear what choice utilities will make he said 
and in the meantime we hold our breath and hope we can make 
it ms bird said 
in ohio if the clean air act amendments dont change 
substantially from where they are now the large mining companies 
will be able to make it and so will some of the mediumsized 
companies she said youll probably see more mergers between 
medium and smallsized companies and some companies will go 
under unfortunately 
the best hope is to accelerate the pace of clean coal technology 
development ms bird said 
the problem now is people are saying well youve been in 
existence in five years why isnt it solved its the perception 
that if you throw enough money at it quickly thatll do it ms 
bird said 
but you cant push science and technology along that fast you 
can accelerate it but you cant make it meet false deadlines 
</TEXT>
