for boston waitress nancy wilson tables are 
empty tips are smaller and taxes are higher 
im an angry voter she says 
she is not alone throughout the recessionstruck northeast 
voters are rebelling against ballooning budgets and taxes as the 
nov 6 elections approach 
already they have drummed out an old generation of political 
incumbents some like democratic governors michael dukakis of 
massachusetts william a oneill of connecticut and madeleine 
kunin of vermont without even casting a ballot all retired 
rather than face the wrath of the voters 
the economic bowling ball has rolled through the northeast and 
many political leaders have gone flying says lee miringoff 
director of the marist college institute for public opinion in 
poughkeepsie ny 
whats more voters in massachusetts are so mad they are 
reviving the tax revolt that began in california in the 1970s and 
spread to massachusetts in 1980 voters then radically slashed 
property taxes levied by town governments and propositions 13 and 
2 became household words 
this time around its known as question 3 a referendum that 
would roll back increases in the state income tax and some fees 
imposed over the past two years and eliminate hundreds of new items 
and services added to the sales tax 
the message nationally if it passes is that the tax revolt 
is still alive and well even in liberal massachusetts says 
william schneider a political analyst with the american enterprise 
institute in washington and a visiting professor at boston college 
with the deficit crisis in washington politicians even 
president bush assume you can pass new taxes and voters will 
understand says schneider so what theyre debating is who 
pays the middle class the rich how the tax burden is 
distributed the message will be not so fast the voters may not 
be reconciled to tax increases even in the midst of a fiscal 
crisis 
the northeast elections promise to be among the nations most 
exciting because of the tax revolt tough economic times tight 
races and the emergence of a new generation of politicians who 
campaigned as outsiders 
and the election could serve as an informal democratic 
presidential referendum for gov mario cuomo of new york and us 
sen bill bradley of new jersey both are expected to be reelected 
over weak challengers but both must win by comfortable margins wo 
keep their political options open 
cuomo seeking a third fouryear term appeared most vulnerable 
this year new yorks credit rating dropped to the third worst in 
the nation only a step above massachusetts and louisiana cuomo 
and the state legislature approved a budget that included a record 
18 billion tax increase 
still as the bowling ball rolled through the northeast mario 
cuomo has remained standing very firmly said marist colleges 
miringoff 
he said that although cuomo is not as popular as he was four 
years ago he is still within striking distance of his record 65 
percent of the vote in 1986 his opponent pierre rinfret has run 
a bumbling illfinanced campaign 
this is not a good time for the northeast unemployment rates 
exceed the national average bankruptcy filings and welfare 
applications have doubled and tripled banks have failed the real 
estate market has collapsed problem loans and repossessed real 
estate have nearly doubled to more than 36 billion 
sales tax and other collections fell short of projections 
yielding large budget deficits tax increases and more layoffs 
massachusetts alone had a record deficit of more than 1 billion in 
the last fiscal year 
three months into the new fiscal year the budget is still 
running astray forcing dukakis to cut spending by another 500 
million all of this in stunning contrast to the massachusetts 
miracle that dukakis boasted of in his failed quest for the 
presidency 
it was a miracle that it lasted as long as it did because of a 
lack of real leadership says gary arnold the owner of process 
control industries inc in taunton a city 35 miles south of 
boston whose economic decline was reversed during the boom years 
process control industries had 200 employees on its payroll 18 
months ago the work force has been cut in half and arnold says the 
company is in a position to move almost at any good opportunity 
the cost of staying in this state is a key issue arnold 
says obviously thats taxes i sure hope the state gets managed 
a lot better theres no attraction to stay here 
in septembers primary arnold and other voters ousted 
democratic incumbents linked to the dukakis administration 
instead as an independent he cast his ballot for the republican 
gubernatorial candidate william weld who beat his own partys 
endorsed candidate 
weld a former assistant us attorney general in the reagan 
administration is in a close race with the democratic candidate 
john silber who is on leave as president of boston university he 
too defeated the partys endorsed candidate campaigning as an 
outsider 
weld supports the tax rollback silber opposes it 
supporters say the dukakis administration increased state 
spending by 92 percent during the last seven years almost three 
times the rate of inflation and left massachusetts with the 
sixthhighest tax burden in the nation 
opponents say the measure would devastate the economy rolling 
back 1 billion already collected and spent and costing the state 
more than 2 billion in the next fiscal year 
domenic bozzotto he broke ranks with the aflcio and threw the 
support of his 5000member local 26 hotel workers union of 
boston behind the tax repeal referendum even more startling was 
the unions endorsement of a republican candidate weld for the 
first time in its 103yearold history 
we never endorsed a republican candidate for anything not 
even dog catcher said bozzotto the president of the union 
our members and their spouses work two three four jobs an 
average hotel worker probably makes somewhere around 17000 to 
20000 a year if they work one job clearly they cant survive 
if we dont grab these guys by the throat at the statehouse and 
make them accountable it will just be business as usual 
that same sentiment is echoed in vermont where kunins 
predecessor republican richard snelling is the favorite with a 
campaign pegged to the states faltering economy he blames kunin 
and in connecticut the democratic partys twodecade hold on 
the governors office is in jeopardy because of the fallout from 
two years of tax hikes totaling more than 1 billion the favorite 
