<TEXT>
caterpillar inc is cashing in on the end of 
us trade sanctions against soviet bloc countries by selling 212 
earthmoving machines to the romanian government for use in coal 
mining 
an analyst said tuesday the deal could be worth 50 million for 
caterpillar and may help the company reclaim eastern bloc markets 
lost to the japanese during the reagan administration embargo 
its a very significant deal for caterpillar said frank 
manfredi of manfredi and associates a buffalo grove illbased 
analyst of the heavy machinery industry 
under a barter agreement announced monday romania will receive 
200 articulated dump trucks 10 tracktype tractors a motor grader 
and a wheelloader 
the equipment will be delivered during the next nine months 
said jeff hawkinson spokesman for caterpillar the worlds largest 
manufacturer of earthmoving equipment 
this will boost caterpillars market share considerably 
manfredi said its a pretty big deal when you consider the world 
market for articulated trucks is about 3000 units annually and 
they just sold 200 or about 7 percent of the world market in one 
deal thats not bad 
caterpillar released few details about the deal but manfredi 
estimated its value at approximately 50 million based on a 
price range of 100000 to 170000 for articulated dump trucks 
commonly used on projects with rough terrain and bad conditions 
the huge offroad vehicles are built in two sections and bend in 
the middle for turning rather than using conventional steering in 
which the wheels turn from sidetoside 
normally these trucks are not used in mining operations 
manfredi said that must mean romanias roads must be in pretty 
bad shape around their mining operations 
manfredi speculated the 10 tractors are likely large bulldozers 
worth upwards of 500000 apiece and the company usually sends a 
supply of spare parts in package deals which would push the value 
even higher 
the cashpoor country will pay for the equipment with 
unspecified romanian goods and services 
thaddeus kopinski director of the office of central and eastern 
europe for the us chamber of commerce in washington said romania 
may be paying caterpillar with forklift trucks 
romanias chief export item is forklift trucks kopinski 
said its part of their materialhandling sector and it fits 
into caterpillars profile 
manfredi said the barter agreement gives caterpillar an 
advantage over competitors who are unable to accept such conditions 
for sales 
prior to the reagan trade embargo caterpillar was the 
supplier of choice to the soviet union and eastern bloc countries 
for years manfredi said 
caterpillar chairman donald fites told a group of visiting 
soviet journalists last month that caterpillar held 85 percent of 
the world market of imported mining equipment in the soviet union 
in 1981 
those customers were forfeited to caterpillars chief 
competitor komatsu and other japanese manufacturers during the 
embargo 
caterpillar has reclaimed about 50 percent of the lost business 
fites said 
manfrei said the numbers are the same for eastern bloc nations 
such as romania 
hawkinson said the sale to romania is the first in more than 10 
years for caterpillar and he called it one of the companys 
biggest deals in eastern europe in a number of years 
hawkinson said caterpillar sees eastern europe as a market with 
great potential because of the regions deteriorated 
infrastructure 
