<TEXT>
a top official of the organization of 
petroleum exporting countries strongly criticized oil consuming 
countries on wednesday for failing to release oil reserves to help 
curb rising oil prices 
opec secretary general subroto said consumer countries have been 
reminded that it might be too late to keep oil prices within 
reasonable bounds if they waited until the fourth quarter of the 
year to release their strategic stocks 
unfortunately these appeals proved fruitless this is a great 
pity and a clear indication that the concept of real 
cooperation between producers and consumers for oil market 
stability still seems to fall on the deaf ears of the majority 
subroto said 
he said that opec has already acted to reduce the danger of an 
oil shortage by pumping out as much oil as it can 
the ball is now in the consumers court it is now up to them 
to bolster the markets defense against an impending energy 
shortage by drawing down on their stocks he told an 
international energy conference in jakarta 
paul vlaanderen representative of the international energy 
agency told the conference earlier that its analysis showed that 
world crude oil markets are still adequately supplied and no 
product shortfalls have been experienced by its members 
vlaanderen said the agency acknowledged that the oil markets are 
nervous in the wake of iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait but the 
situation still is manageable 
he said prices are fluctuating based upon fears of war or hopes 
for peace in the persian gulf and the current strains on the oil 
system are unlikely to be remedied by a simple drawdown of iea 
strategic stocks 
it is a political phenomenon and not a supplydemand 
fundamental which drives the market physical shortages do not 
explain present price fluctuations he said 
subroto told the conference that opecs total sustainable 
production capacity would increase from the current 28 million 
barrels to 34 million barrels a day in 1995 
he said nonopec production would remain unchanged or fall 
slightly by the end of century and oil supply from the communist 
countries would decline largely because of lower soviet production 
and higher consumption in china 
demand for opec oil increased from 1545 million barrels a day 
in 1985 to 2191 million barrels in 1989 this year the figure is 
expected to reach 23 million barrels 
helga steeg executive director of the international energy 
agency said member countries of the organization for economic 
cooperation and development would grow more dependent on imports 
due not only to rising oil demand but also to a decline in their 
oil production 
mrs steeg said in a prepared statement that oecds dependence 
on imports could rise from 53 percent in 1988 to 70 percent by 
2005 
the oecd members include the united states germany japan and 
other industrial nations 
