helmeted and harnessed du pont co 
workers grunt groan and sweat as they scale a 40foot wall climb 
a skinny 30foot pole and zip down a 300foot wire 
they cheer each other on with shouts of you can do it 
were behind ya how do you feel 
with a break for a brownbag lunch theyve finished the first 
half of the daylong ropes course the introduction to du pont 
fibers departments playing to win seminars and empowered 
learning teams 
the idea is to keep fibers competitive and increase productivity 
of employees who can work better with supervisors and each other 
said clifford e nix fibers development director 
the company is spending at least 23 million on the effort it 
paid 13 million for the 45acre campsite on the elk river in 
northeastern maryland it leases resorts for fibers employees to 
take the same training at two sites in north carolina and one in 
virginia and tennessee all of the sites are near du pont fibers 
plants 
the seminars four days for managers and two days for employees 
with their managers are similar to the wilderness training 
courses that became popular among corporate executives in the 
1980s 
but du ponts program which began about four months ago is 
unique because it is inhouse and is required for all 20000 
employees in the fibers department which makes polyester nylon 
spandex and other materials 
the company has contracted with pecos river learning centers of 
santa fe nm to provide the training 
what we want to create is a work environment where peoples 
values can truly be expressed with the team and having an 
environment where those values can be brought to the surface and 
having the freedom to express that nix said 
that means changing management style 
the key to the success of this whole effort is the willingness 
of the leadership to embrace change themselves theres room for 
change but the leadership has to let go and shift our behavior and 
our roles as leaders in the organization nix said 
there have been a lot of companies experimenting with what we 
call employee involvement programs its based upon an 
established theory that if employees are involved in the 
decisionmaking process morale and productivity will go up said 
douglas m mccabe a labor relations expert and professor at 
georgetown university in washington 
james h wilbur a securities analyst with smith barney harris 
upham amp co said the timing is right because fibers earnings are 
likely to fall short of last years so if you can get the people 
to work together and be productive it couldnt come at a better 
time than when things are tight 
he said earnings in the fibers department which represent 
nearly a quarter of du ponts total profits have been hurt by a 
rise in foreign competition and raw materials costs the divisions 
first quarter profit fell to 168 million from 173 million last 
year second quarter earnings dropped to 157 million from 182 
million 
miles overholt a management consultant and family therapist 
said the program can be successful if du pont sustains enthusiasm 
among its employees 
any kind of program thats out on the market now such as 
pecos river are great as a kickoff because the message is clear 
its direct its concise the hard part is continuing it said 
overholt president of applied organizational development inc of 
palmyra nj 
mccabe of georgetown university said the new approach can be 
sustained only if top management is totally dedicated to the 
proposition of employee involvement 
trust has to be a very strong value of the organization 
trusting each other in that work environment industry as a whole 
has got to embrace that value nix said 
when the training began employees were skeptical and it was 
difficult to get them to attend now the courses are booked 
through june 1991 
more than 3000 employees have been trained at the sites since 
the first one opened in june in virginia at natural bridge 
each week that goes by my conviction grows its much 
different today than the way i felt in may or june you wondered if 
people were going to get on the bus to go to the sites nix said 
people who havent gone through it generally dont know what 
to think of it those who have gone through it there has been a 
good response but there still appears to be a waitandsee 
attitude said nancy tidona du pont spokeswoman 
nix said the teams will continue training with 10 fourhour 
seminars in the workplace spread over 18 months after visiting the 
wilderness site 
when the entire department has completed all of the training he 
said he expects fibers to be in a more competitive position for 
the future i expect more unity and more productivity 
but the program hasnt been without its problems george w 
martin a 58yeraold plant supervisor died of a heart attack in 
september after completing one of ropes course activities 
nix said the only other accident has been a sprained ankle 
employees with medical problems are excused from the exercises he 
said 
after each activity the teams are debriefed to discuss how the 
activity relates to their work 
the concept behind three people hooked together to scale a 
40foot wall is to make a group decision on whether to make it to 
the top there should be no hard feelings if a member does not want 
to go on tidona said 
you can only go as far as your weakest team members she 
said 
i expect when its all over ill probably be a little more 
open with my peers and be more supportive of others employee 
richard block said on the first day of a recent fourday seminar 
