<TEXT>
a super highway of oil has been tapped 
in southeastern wyoming by a drilling technique that could spur an 
oil boom in the region a petroleum expert said wednesday 
the find announced wednesday by union pacific resources co of 
fort worth texas lies in the niobrara formation 18 miles 
northeast of cheyenne 
a 21hour test of the well produced 1462 barrels of crude the 
greatest daily production of any wyoming well according to 
officials 
the company a subsidiary of union pacific corp achieved the 
results by boring into the formation horizontally instead of using 
traditional vertical techniques which would have produced as little 
as 50 barrels per day according to chuck farmer a petroleum 
engineer with the wyoming oil and gas commission 
the find will result in a miniboom he said 
unlike vertical wells that bore straight down and miss pockets 
of oil on either side of the well horizontal wells start 
vertically but the drill bit gradually is turned 90 degrees to 
traverse the rock formation this enables the drill to encounter 
multiple fractures filled with oil that might be missed by a 
vertical drill 
farmer said horizontal drilling appears to be catching on in 
wyoming in 1989 the oil and gas commission received only one 
applicatio 
</TEXT>
