a second eastern airlines foreman at kennedy 
airport has quietly pleaded guilty to falsifying aircraft safety 
and maintenance records and has agreed to cooperate with 
authorities according to court records 
michael hennessey easterns general foreman at the airport 
admitted to conspiring with other airline employees to falsify log 
books work cards and computer records in a scheme that allegedly 
allowed unsafe aircraft to carry passengers 
hennessey who faces a maximum sentence of five years in prison 
and a 250000 fine pleaded guilty at an oct 9 hearing before 
us district judge i leo glasser of brooklyn 
an eastern spokeswoman karen ceremsak said the airline had no 
comment on hennesseys plea 
a cooperation agreement was filed as part of his plea 
agreement hennesseys lawyer henry putzel said wednesday he 
has been and will continue to be fully cooperative with the 
government 
hennessey who was not charged in a 60count criminal 
indictment that was unsealed in july and accuses the airline and 
several top managers of routinely ignoring vital repairs pleaded 
guilty and remains free on his own recognizance 
hennessey and the other defendants caused aircraft that were 
not properly maintained and repaired to fly and carry unsuspecting 
passengers court documents alleged 
according to court records the scheme was directed by two top 
eastern executives former vice president edward upton and thomas 
lewis who was the maintenance director of easterns northern 
region airports allegedly employed intimidation and coercion 
to force company workers to avoid and minimize flight delays and 
cancellations by falsifying aircraft maintenance records 
prosecutors allege that records were altered to make it appear 
scheduled maintenance and corrective repairs had been done when in 
fact they had not been 
hennessey also admitted to lying to federal aviation 
administration authorities investigating the eastern scheme which 
allegedly took place from july 1985 to october 1989 at kennedy and 
la guardia airports in new york hartsfield international airport 
in atlanta and eastern headquarters in miami 
the criminal indictment was unprecedented in the airline 
industry and came as eastern was trying to rebuild its faltering 
service regain passengers and reorganize in bankruptcy court after 
bitter labor disputes 
the case is scheduled to go to trial at the federal courthouse 
in brooklyn in january 
in july a former eastern foreman named in the indictment 
pleaded guilty and agreed to testify 
elia dragone of jersey city nj the first eastern employee to 
plead guilty said the scheme was orchestrated by his superiors at 
the airline 
he admitted to conspiracy and obstructing an faa investigation 
into the airline 
