<TEXT>
american telephone amp telegraph co and 
kokusai denshin denwa of japan on wednesday announced they are 
studying the possibility of building a new telephone cable across 
the pacific ocean 
the proposed cable system which would link the united states 
and japan would use optical amplifier technology and operate at 
eight times the capacity of existing fiberoptic cables atampt said 
in a statement 
the new cable network system would help international carriers 
provide telecommunications services in their countries said david 
bikle a spokesman for atampt 
optical amplifiers which are segments of an optical fiber that 
contain the element erbium boost lightwave signals without 
converting them to electrons and back to light as is done in 
conventional systems 
the worlds first fiber optic transoceanic system went into 
service in 1988 and is capable of handling 40000 calls at once 
bikle said 
the new optical amplifier cable system expected to be in 
service in 1996 would be able to handle 600000 calls he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

